<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,1161,1404]" pageId="3" pageNumber="560">
This genus of 120 fungus-feeding species worldwide is one of the largest genera of 
<taxonomicName authority="(ThripsWiki 2019)" authorityName="ThripsWiki" authorityYear="2019" baseAuthorityName="ThripsWiki" baseAuthorityYear="2019" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="560" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Phlaeothripinae">
Phlaeothripinae (
<bibRefCitation accessDate="2019-05-01" author="ThripsWiki" pageId="3" pageNumber="560" publicationUrl="http://thrips.info/wiki/" refId="ref7542" refString="ThripsWiki (2019) providing information on the World's thrips. Available from: http: // thrips. info / wiki / (accessed 1 May 2019)" title="providing information on the World's thrips" type="url" year="2019">ThripsWiki 2019</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. The species frequently exhibit considerable dimorphism associated with sex and also with wing length, and there is often great variation in body size often involving allometry in some structural characters of males. Consequently, it is difficult to identify many of species of this widespread genus, as many are known only from few specimens (
<bibRefCitation author="Hoddle" box="[283,496,1305,1331]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Hoddle" pageId="3" pageNumber="560" refId="ref6313" refString="Hoddle, M., Mound, L. A. &amp; Paris, D. (2019) Thysanoptera Californica. An identification and information system to thrips in California. Available from: https: // keys. lucidcentral. org / keys / v 3 / thrips _ of _ california _ 2019 / (accessed 10 July 2019)" type="url" year="2019">
Hoddle 
<emphasis box="[374,430,1305,1331]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="560">et al.</emphasis>
2019
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Mound" box="[508,657,1305,1331]" firstAuthor="Mound" pageId="3" pageNumber="560" pagination="137 - 152" refId="ref6972" refString="Mound, L. A. (2017) Intra-specific structural variation among Hawaiian Hoplothrips (Thysanoptera, Phlaeothripidae), with ten new synonymies and one new species. ZooKeys, (722), 137 - 152. https: // doi. org / 10.3897 / zookeys. 722.22131" type="journal article" year="2017">Mound 2017</bibRefCitation>
). These thrips are usually found on dead branches, although some are associated with leaf litter. From this genus only one unidentified species (
<figureCitation box="[992,1060,1341,1368]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–12" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1890,1915]" captionTargetBox="[202,1383,184,1862]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[197,1390,179,1862]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–12. Fungus feeding thrips species of Iran (1) Hindsiothrips sisakhti (female); (2) Idiothrips bellus (female); (3) Hoplandrothrips bidens (female); (4) Liophloeothrips arganicus (female); (5) Hoplothrips (female); (6) Cephalothrips monilicornis (female); (7) Cephalothrips coxalis (female); (8) Allothrips bournieri (female); (9) Stictothrips farsi sp. n. (female); (10) Stictothrips farsi sp. n. (male); (11) Pseudocryptothrips meridionalis (female); (12) Megathrips flavipes (female)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3364946/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="560">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
) is recorded from 
<collectingCountry box="[1275,1323,1342,1368]" name="Iran" pageId="3" pageNumber="560">Iran</collectingCountry>
, with two females taken in the north of 
<collectingCountry box="[479,524,1378,1404]" name="Iran" pageId="3" pageNumber="560">Iran</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Jalali Sendi" box="[539,801,1377,1403]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Jalali Sendi" pageId="3" pageNumber="560" pagination="325 - 329" refId="ref6376" refString="Jalali Sendi, J., Zibaee, I. &amp; Minaei, K. (2011) An Investigation on thrips fauna of Guilan province, north of Iran (Insecta: Thysanoptera). Munis Entomology &amp; Zoology, 6, 325 - 329." type="journal article" year="2011">
Jalali Sendi 
<emphasis box="[678,734,1377,1403]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="560">et al.</emphasis>
2011
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
